00:45.233 --> 01:02.235
Detroit Renaissance, whose ambition was to 
redevelop downtown Detroit the Renaissance

01:02.536 --> 01:08.345
Center, which is a large, major urban mixed-use 
project. It was one of the things that we

01:08.365 --> 01:12.973
stimulated to be done when we were there. And then I 
followed my interests into the Newtown movement

01:15.056 --> 01:28.898
of the late 60s and early 70s by joining a company 
called the Newfields Development Corporation.

01:30.346 --> 01:45.425
That was in 1974, which was, and Newfields was a 
4,000-acre new community, HUD new community,

01:30.346 --> 01:45.425
just outside of Dayton, Ohio, in a little town 
called Trotwood, Ohio. Trotwood. Trotwood.

01:47.107 --> 01:48.729
T-R-O-T-W-O-W-D. I had been following new towns 
virtually my entire career when I was with

01:48.950 --> 02:00.184
Minneapolis Housing Redevelopment Authority, 
which was from Oh, let's see. That was about 1960. I

02:05.007 --> 02:12.195
got out of graduate school. Where were you? I was in 
graduate school at the University of Minnesota in

02:13.216 --> 02:17.021
Minneapolis. Were you in architecture or urban? 
Public administration. So it was an MPA you got in?

02:21.767 --> 02:22.668
I got an MPA. And I took a lot of courses in the School 
of Architecture and Planning because I had a real

02:23.068 --> 02:30.357
interest in it. And while I was at the University of 
Minnesota, I did an internship as part of the

02:31.366 --> 02:38.238
public administration program there. I did an 
internship with Minneapolis Housing Authority.

02:43.608 --> 02:51.282
Having grown up in New York and seeing the public 
housing projects that were developed there, I was

02:43.608 --> 02:51.282
always amazed at how rational man could develop 
those things. And I was curious enough that when

02:54.348 --> 03:11.554
offered an internship, I asked them to place me 
with the housing authority so I could see what kind

02:54.348 --> 03:11.554
of idiotic policies might lead to that kind of 
inhumane kind of habitat development. It turned

03:11.575 --> 03:17.924
out the Minneapolis Housing Authority has done 
some of the more outstanding public housing

03:11.575 --> 03:17.924
development in the country. And I was pleased to 
have been able to And then when I graduated, go on to

03:21.265 --> 03:32.499
work there and actually develop some of what has 
been recognized as some of the more outstanding

03:21.265 --> 03:32.499
senior citizen housing in the country. So I never 
did find out why New York City developed the kind of

03:32.559 --> 03:37.225
housing that it did. I think it was more economics 
and pressure for scale than anything else. But at

03:44.154 --> 03:49.180
that time, that was the late 60s, two new towns were 
getting started. One of them was Jonathan,

03:49.598 --> 03:56.869
southwest of Minneapolis in a small town called 
Chaska, Minnesota. And then the first new town in

03:58.311 --> 04:15.876
town under the HUD program called Cedar 
Riverside, which is on the west bank of the

03:58.311 --> 04:15.876
Mississippi River, just adjoining the 
University of Minnesota. While I was living and

04:16.261 --> 04:22.450
working there, going to school there, I was able to 
see what was going on. Was there any involvement by

04:22.470 --> 04:27.137
the faculty in that kind of development that you 
noticed? Well, the principals were actually

04:27.157 --> 04:31.003
professors at the university. They started it. 
And so, yeah, there was a lot of involvement. And

04:38.234 --> 04:43.382
then the New York State Urban Development 
Corporation, which I went to after, of the

04:43.835 --> 04:52.723
Minneapolis Housing Redevelopment Authority, 
was the developer of four, either three or four new

04:43.835 --> 04:52.723
towns.

04:55.926 --> 04:56.507
Actually, three. I think there was one in 
Rochester, two in Rochester. No, I take that back.

05:02.812 --> 05:11.260
One in Rochester, one in Buffalo, New York, and 
then a new town in town in the middle of the East

05:02.812 --> 05:11.260
River called Roosevelt Island. which the first 
two of them never got off the ground to speak of, but

05:12.337 --> 05:21.686
Roosevelt Island or Roosevelt Island did. And it 
is a major in-town development and very

05:21.707 --> 05:27.793
successful today. So I saw those, although I was 
not directly involved in working there. I saw what

05:34.019 --> 05:35.460
was going on. So when I had a chance to become 
involved with a new town, Newfields in Ohio, I

05:41.800 --> 05:54.039
jumped at the opportunity and was involved with 
the planning and initial stages of development.

05:54.881 --> 06:01.211
But moreover, I was brought in to a large extent 
because of my background in the public sector. And

06:01.231 --> 06:09.023
Newfields was in the negotiations with HUD 
regarding the project agreement and the

06:01.231 --> 06:09.023
financing. So for about a year and a half, I spent a 
lot of time in Washington with HUD negotiating the

06:09.982 --> 06:17.633
project agreement. In behalf of Newfields. In 
behalf of Newfields. And we were successful. We

06:24.964 --> 06:30.853
arranged a $14 million commitment for Newfields.

06:33.417 --> 06:38.284
And unfortunately for the project and most of the 
projects and in the Hutt program, they came on

06:38.804 --> 06:48.679
stream just as the economy was nosediving into a 
very deep recession that lasted from 1973 to 1975.

06:49.400 --> 06:55.569
And Newfieldsâ€” So you were in Washington about 72, 
72? Well, I was in Ohio, but I was traveling to

06:55.589 --> 07:02.380
Washington, going back and forth quite a bit. And 
Newfields opened and closed. opened in, I think it

07:05.720 --> 07:12.529
was the fall of 74, the beginning of 75, and shut 
down in the fall of 75. It was just too severe a

07:12.690 --> 07:21.041
recession for it to withstand. And Newfield, the 
developer at Newfield, did not have the financial

07:22.203 --> 07:32.236
wherewithal to sustain that project. And as we get 
on and talk about the Woodlands, we'll see that's

07:32.257 --> 07:35.541
one of the significant differences between the 
Woodlands and the other projects in the HUD

07:36.432 --> 07:47.805
program, namely stronger financial backing than 
any of the other projects have. Yeah, that's what

07:47.825 --> 07:56.175
they would want to be sure to work on a little bit, is 
that since you've had such a very broad view of the

07:47.825 --> 07:56.175
world, is to prepare that world for this. Yeah. So 
I, continuing with my personal escapades, I left

08:04.495 --> 08:15.572
Newfield in 75, and I did consulting among a number 
of the new communities in the HUD program. They

08:15.592 --> 08:20.759
were all having difficulties because of the time 
and the recession. So I consulted for quite a while

08:21.540 --> 08:33.979
with Park Forest South, which is a HUD Newtowns in 
that community south of Chicago. And then HUD

08:35.933 --> 08:52.032
asked me to come to Washington and consult on 
virtually a full-time basis to help them with what

08:35.933 --> 08:52.032
became workout attempts on about five new 
communities. Shenandoah, south of Atlanta, and

08:53.653 --> 09:01.302
several others, which I did. And I spent about a 
year in Washington doing that. And it was when I was

09:05.667 --> 09:11.876
in Washington that they asked me to do some work on 
the Woodlands. The Woodlands had applied for a

09:12.717 --> 09:17.864
fairly significant grant to develop the Trade 
Center. And so I found myself representing HUD in

09:18.825 --> 09:23.632
those negotiations. Met Rob Lapp, who was vice 
president for governmental affairs, who was

09:23.812 --> 09:33.345
representing the Woodlands Corporation. And

09:35.198 --> 09:44.508
HUD wound up giving the Woodlands a $650,000 grant 
for the Trade Center. And when that was all over and

09:44.528 --> 09:51.275
my work was winding down at HUD, there was an 
opening here in Rob Lapp's department. And he

09:51.295 --> 09:54.558
invited me to come down and visit the Woodlands. 
And I did. And I wound up working for him. That's

09:59.363 --> 10:00.844
when you were on trade? Yeah. I came in. My official 
start date was March 1st of 1977

10:05.084 --> 10:16.620
as Director of Governmental Affairs. And in that 
position, I was responsible for a lot of grant

10:18.663 --> 10:29.218
work, HUD liaison work. local governmental 
relations, working with the county, state

10:30.937 --> 10:39.689
agencies, and regional council of governments. 
By grant work, you mean you wrote proposals? Yeah,

10:42.533 --> 10:45.317
I wrote grant applications. I think personally, 
over the years, I've brought in about $16 or $17

10:45.397 --> 10:57.093
million worth of grant proceeds to this 
corporation. Overall, I think the company has

10:59.573 --> 11:02.957
gotten something in excess of $30 million. And so I 
wrote all the proposals to HUD for community

11:04.459 --> 11:13.350
development block grants. I have gotten grants 
from the state for parks and participated in

11:13.370 --> 11:28.129
writing grant applications to the Department of 
Energy for various demonstration grants. So was

11:29.527 --> 11:33.814
that one of the reasons why LAP was interested in 
you, or do you know? Yeah, I guess. But you never

11:35.497 --> 11:38.822
actually discussed it in that sense. Well, my 
public background was something they were

11:40.445 --> 11:55.770
looking for here, because the Woodlands, being 
such a large project, has to deal with public

11:40.445 --> 11:55.770
agencies all the time. But at that time, We were in a 
virtual partnership with HUD. And the

12:00.955 --> 12:05.381
corporation, I think, wanted to have somebody who 
knew how to deal with it. When I was at the

12:05.421 --> 12:10.228
Minneapolis Housing Authority, I was dealing 
with HUD all the time. Actually, I was dealing with

12:10.248 --> 12:12.210
predecessor agencies. That was even before HUD 
was created. But in the areas of housing, public

12:15.695 --> 12:23.505
housing, low and moderate income housing, they 
needed that here. We, as part of the program, were

12:23.525 --> 12:27.310
required to develop low- and moderate-income 
housing. We're supposed to develop housing that

12:30.398 --> 12:37.365
would represent a cross-section of the Houston 
demography. And one of the criticisms HUD had of

12:38.466 --> 12:44.553
the Woodlands is it wasn't building enough 
affordable housing. It wasn't building any low-

12:44.573 --> 12:47.216
and moderate-income housing. I came out of the 
public sector, a housing background, with the New

12:51.623 --> 12:54.206
York State Urban Development Corporation. I was 
building housing across New York State,

12:54.226 --> 12:58.892
public-type housing. And when I came here, that's 
another thing that I did. We have now...

13:02.256 --> 13:10.786
Well, let me put it this way. When HUD was still 
funding those programs, one out of every five

13:11.387 --> 13:19.977
units that was built in the woodlands was a 
subsidized unit. rent subsidized or mortgage

13:20.193 --> 13:23.358
subsidized. And those were my responsibilities.

13:27.804 --> 13:48.775
So we've developed either directly as the 
developer or through other companies that

13:27.804 --> 13:48.775
specialized in that, I think, well, over 1,000, 
probably closer to 1,200 subsidized units in the

13:27.804 --> 13:48.775
woodlands. And I was responsible for it. for doing 
that. So in some cases, I was the project manager

13:51.507 --> 14:00.078
actually developing those units for the company. 
Or I went out and sought out developers who would

14:00.098 --> 14:07.649
come in and do it because of specialties that they 
had. And also, I brought that kind of expertise

14:08.590 --> 14:19.765
into a subsidiary or an affiliate corporation 
that we have called Mitchell Mortgage Company,

14:08.590 --> 14:19.765
where I set up a commercial division specializing 
in the use of government financing,

14:20.082 --> 14:37.145
tax-exempt bond financing, industrial revenue 
bonds, and government housing programs. Are you

14:37.166 --> 14:41.491
on, let's say, the board of Mitch Morgans now, or 
are you directly involved? No, I'm not. Let me

14:42.253 --> 14:42.953
interrupt you. One of the questions you raised, 
you said HUD's concern was that there was

14:42.973 --> 14:49.903
insufficient or that there was no At that time, no. 
None? None. Now, I've sensed in discussions with

14:53.972 --> 15:06.891
some others that

14:53.972 --> 15:06.891
Mr. Mitchell always planned, however, to have a 
community of broad economic base. Was that

15:06.911 --> 15:19.671
because of the economic situation that that had 
been, I don't want to say neglected, that has all

15:06.911 --> 15:19.671
kinds of values associated with it, but that the 
developers were pushing another segment of the

15:06.911 --> 15:19.671
economy rather than... Or was it because there was 
no funding from HUD? Well, I think it's twofold.

15:27.667 --> 15:33.758
HUD was recalcitrant in funding the programs that 
are promised. And it wasn't until probably 76, or I

15:33.778 --> 15:40.731
think 76 was probably about the year, when they 
actually came through on their promises to make

15:41.420 --> 15:56.819
grants and other assistance available to the 
Newtowns to carry out the social objectives of the

15:41.420 --> 15:56.819
Newtown program. And that only came about because 
there were several developers among the 13

15:57.540 --> 16:10.296
projects that were in the program that finally 
went to Congress and said, we've entered this

15:57.540 --> 16:10.296
program taking on certain obligations that 
developers rarely, if ever, take on, and they're

16:11.204 --> 16:17.675
of a social nature. Economic integration, racial 
integration,

16:19.658 --> 16:34.883
the building in the job base as well as housing, 
those are social objectives, the environment.

16:35.234 --> 16:40.862
developing in a way that's much more costly 
because you're trying to protect the

16:35.234 --> 16:40.862
environment. And HUD had promised the developers 
financial assistance to help carry these out

16:40.882 --> 17:03.016
because you cannot absorb those costs in the 
regular profit picture of a private development.

17:03.036 --> 17:04.498
It just can't be done. And HUD, as I said, reneged on 
that until several of the developers who were...

17:11.385 --> 17:31.050
There was an association of Newtown developers 
that would get together periodically, and

17:11.385 --> 17:31.050
several of them were very good in understanding 
the Washington scene and how to get things done

17:11.385 --> 17:31.050
politically. And they went to Congress and got... 
If we're up to HUD, half of the stuff that we're

17:34.600 --> 17:39.084
doing here in the Woodlands today never would have 
been done. So in summary, this was actually HUD's

17:39.104 --> 17:43.288
failure then, is what you're perceiving. I think 
it was. Now HUD, on the other hand, had a

17:44.869 --> 17:51.235
philosophical difference also with the way the 
Woodlands got started.

17:54.298 --> 18:02.025
HUD would have liked to have seen this project 
start out with only low and moderate income

17:54.298 --> 18:02.025
housing. While HUD agreed contractually that 
there would be the entire spectrum of housing

18:02.917 --> 18:16.030
price in the Woodlands, the staff at HUD never 
really agreed with that. And they considered it an

18:16.050 --> 18:21.215
anathema when they would come down here and see a 
golf course. And they said, why is the federal

18:21.655 --> 18:24.218
government doing that? Well, the Woodlands 
Corporation, being a developer, understood that

18:32.431 --> 18:38.438
if you started out just with the low end of housing, 
you'd never get the cross section. You would

18:39.880 --> 18:44.566
stigmatize the Woodlands as being another HUD 
project. And they wouldn't differentiate it

18:44.586 --> 18:52.956
between a new town and a low income community that 
HUD has sponsored somewhere else. So there was a

18:54.298 --> 19:01.847
strategy of building upper end housing as well as 
middle end and as well as some affordable housing.

19:06.473 --> 19:09.016
Rylan Home was building in here from day one. They 
were building housing that started in the low 20s.

19:12.421 --> 19:17.748
So we were not devoid of the lower end of the 
housing. But HUD was chapped at the fact that we

19:17.768 --> 19:26.259
were building, in those days, what were 
considered to be expensive homes. Well, the fact

19:26.279 --> 19:32.087
is the Woodlands established its reputation in 
the marketplace as being a good quality

19:32.388 --> 19:35.171
community. And because of that, we were able to 
sell $200,000, $300,000, $400,000 houses, as

19:36.272 --> 19:44.960
well as $20,000, $30,000, and $40,000 homes. And 
this is unparalleled in Houston and unparalleled

19:45.060 --> 19:51.786
in the country. That's good. That's a good 
delineation. Now, do you think that character is

19:55.430 --> 19:58.052
still holding in the Woodlands? Absolutely. With 
the balance? Absolutely. It's getting harder to

20:01.615 --> 20:04.839
do because of the absence of grants. We used to get 
grants to do the infrastructure in areas where

20:04.879 --> 20:21.102
we're going to build the low-end product, what we 
call production builders, Ryland. Today it's

20:21.122 --> 20:22.564
Ryland and Pulte. But in those days, Ryland and 
there were some other builders building in that

20:23.305 --> 20:29.994
price range. And what we would do is by virtue of the 
fact that we had grants to build the

20:31.602 --> 20:47.441
infrastructure, we would then stipulate to the 
builder that their price range had to reflect the

20:31.602 --> 20:47.441
fact that we could sell the lots to them cheaper. We 
did not want them to get a windfall profit because

20:47.461 --> 20:56.592
we would, in effect, discount the lots to the 
builder by virtue of the grants that we received.

20:57.493 --> 20:59.095
We had a lower cost basis. We passed that savings on 
to the builder and then stipulated that they had to

20:59.446 --> 21:09.380
keep their sales price within certain ranges, 
which we had agreed with HUD. Did HUD understand

21:09.400 --> 21:10.722
what was happening? Oh, yeah. Sure. This was all. 
Yeah. And that's why they gave us the grants. So

21:15.709 --> 21:23.039
everything we did in that regard had been reviewed 
with HUD and pre-approved by HUD. And our

21:23.760 --> 21:27.445
department... And then when he left the company, I 
took over the department. It was to a large extent,

21:34.346 --> 21:42.216
we were that linkage between the development 
operations and HUD. We were responsible for all

21:42.236 --> 21:53.049
the financial reporting to HUD and all of the 
contract administration and approvals that were

21:42.236 --> 21:53.049
needed. It was a very laborious and tedious 
partnership working with the federal

21:57.243 --> 22:00.368
government. One, I don't recommend to any 
developer because HUD is trying to protect what it

22:00.448 --> 22:13.669
perceives to be the financial or the public 
interest properly. So I don't fall for that. But

22:17.054 --> 22:22.963
the way they go about their business is very slow 
and painstaking. And a developer has to be

22:23.888 --> 22:30.097
responsive to market conditions, which change 
quickly. I mean, we can see today that an incident

22:30.117 --> 22:45.238
in the Middle East can affect the United States 
economy very directly, and real estate is

22:30.117 --> 22:45.238
affected accordingly. So a developer has to be 
able to change gears quickly. HUD is unable. The

22:50.322 --> 22:52.885
federal government is unable to change gears 
quickly. And that was, to a large extent, a very

22:53.506 --> 23:04.698
frustrating relationship.

23:04.719 --> 23:13.048
And each party was probably right from their own 
perspective, but it was a difficult partnership

23:04.719 --> 23:13.048
to carry out. Essentially, the HUD association 
was seized roughly around 82, 84? 83 was when the

23:20.054 --> 23:25.199
final termination agreement was signed. We 
worked on that for about two years. They told us a

23:27.501 --> 23:32.365
couple of years before that that they wanted to get 
out of the business. We were the only project at

23:32.525 --> 23:43.795
that time that was continuing, that was honoring 
the schedule of repayment of the ventures, that

23:32.525 --> 23:43.795
was reporting to HUD. As I said, before I came to the 
Woodlands Corporation, I had gone to HUD as a

23:44.028 --> 23:50.215
consultant on our workout situation. Well, 
mostly what we did was to figure out how HUD could

23:50.795 --> 24:00.446
minimize its losses because there weren't very 
many viable projects. Financially, there were

