42:04.491 --> 42:05.272
dealing with it.

42:09.016 --> 42:19.990
Community associations as a

42:09.016 --> 42:19.990
reasonably widespread phenomenon is only about 
18 years old. 17, 18 years old. They really started

42:23.245 --> 42:26.969
coming into play around 1973. And in 1973, there 
were only about 500 community associations

42:28.690 --> 42:36.417
around the country. And now there are hundreds of 
thousands, tens of thousands. I mean, we've got,

42:41.702 --> 42:46.767
we estimate, 4,000 to 5,000 community 
associations in the Houston area alone. And there

42:48.188 --> 42:53.033
has developed a profession of community 
management in a national organization called the

42:53.840 --> 43:01.710
Community Associations Institute, which trains 
people to be community managers.

43:04.273 --> 43:14.306
And I'm personally very active

43:04.273 --> 43:14.306
in that, and it's been a good experience. 
Transition is the process of turning a community

43:14.326 --> 43:22.497
association control from the developer to to the 
residents of the community. It happens in condo

43:26.860 --> 43:32.708
associations, townhouse associations, and 
homeowners associations. It typically takes

43:33.329 --> 43:42.721
place when the development is about 85% 
completed.

43:43.482 --> 43:51.433
And this was a convention which has been 
institutionalized by Fannie Mae and Ginnie Mae

43:43.482 --> 43:51.433
and HUD and so forth. So a developer has to do it. The 
rationale there is during the actual phases of

43:53.054 --> 44:01.464
development, the developer needs control of his 
project. He needs to be able to make business

44:01.484 --> 44:12.096
decisions about what's going to be developed, 
when it's going to be developed, how it's going to

44:01.484 --> 44:12.096
be developed, design decisions, and so forth. And 
a community association is considered to be an

44:13.458 --> 44:19.225
important part of development. It's very 
important to the marketing of the project. more so

44:23.058 --> 44:26.101
on the larger projects, less so on the smaller 
projects. But nevertheless, setting it up so that

44:26.121 --> 44:36.951
it's economically viable and all of the covenants 
and the bylaws and all of that are done properly.

44:37.072 --> 44:39.114
And that's the reason it's left in the developer's 
hands.

44:41.876 --> 44:48.863
But come 85% of completion,

44:41.876 --> 44:48.863
the developer turns it over to the residents. The 
authorities, like Fannie Mae and Judy Mayfield,

44:52.089 --> 45:02.602
that the developers' interests have been 
substantially protected, and it's time to turn it

44:52.089 --> 45:02.602
over. And in those situations, generally what 
they're doing is turning over the assets of the

45:02.622 --> 45:18.462
association, the common property, the open 
space, common areas, swimming pools, tennis

45:02.622 --> 45:18.462
courts, things like that. They also turn over the 
books and records of the association and any funds

45:20.315 --> 45:32.334
that the association has, bank accounts, which 
the developers hold. When the Woodlands was

45:32.354 --> 45:36.521
